photo.description: At top: Sum Fran. Mymeri Thorunien[sis]. 1558. [Dated 16th-century ms. ownership inscription of humanist Franciscus Mymerus (ca. 1500-1592) of Toruń, Poland, who published a Dictionarium trium linguarum (Latin, German and Polish) in 1528. Established heading: Mymerus, Franciscus] At center: Casparus Elcner Martisburg[ensis]: pastor Neostadiens[is]: dono dedit Magistro Melchiori Poppio pastori Holens[i]: necessitudinis ergo Anno 1596. [Dated late 16th-century ms. inscription recording the gift of this volume from Caspar Elcner, a native of Merseburg, Germany, and pastor at Neustadtl (now Jezvé, Czech Republic) to Melchior Poppe (fl. 1570-1597), pastor at Hohlen (now Holany, Czech Republic) near Böhmisch-Leipa (now Česká Lípa). Poppe was a Catholic priest and a member of the Cistercian order who later converted to Lutheranism, under which confession he served at Hohlen. Poppe published Latin verses on the occasion of two weddings, one each in 1570 and 1571 (cf. VD 16 P 4255, ZV 12671), and a pair of funerary sermons in 1597 (cf. VD 16 ZV 12672). DNB heading: Poppe, Melchior] At bottom: Ex libris Antonij Mitteiss [Ownership inscription of Antonius Mitteiss.] Penn Libraries call number: Inc G-36 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Binder's stamp of Chambolle-Duru, the 19th-century binding firm founded by René Victor Chambolle (1834-1898) and Hippolyte Duru (d. 1884) in 1861. Duru left the partnership in 1863, but Chambolle continued to produce bindings under the name "Chambolle-Duru". After his death, his son René (1873-1915) took over the firm. photo.description: Ex libris. Gilbert R. Redgrave The Elms Beckenham, Kent. Feb. 1895 Note This is a fine copy of the first illustrated edition of Euclid, and it is probably the most magnificent work of the series produced by E. Ratdolt during his stay at Venice, from 1476 to 1486. It is No 26 of my "Bibliography" of this period of Ratdolt's activity. The leatherwork of the cover was designed and executed by me, and the binding is by Lachnsdorf. G.R.R. Pollard he coedited the STC, a standard reference work for books printed in the United Kingdom or in English elsewhere between 1475 and 1640. photo.description: [...] Pancracio Lafita BARBASTRO [Partially illegible blind stamp of Pancracio (sometimes Pancrazio) Lafita, a priest in Barbastro, Spain. These documents identify him as "benefiziado-penitenziario de la Santa Iglesia Catedral de Barbastro" [curate-penitentiary of the Catedral de Santa María de la Asunción de Barbastro], as well as having some kind of supervisory authority over the parish of San Hipólito in 1891. By the turn of the twentieth century he was teaching at the seminary in Barbastro, where he appears to have been responsible for discovering the ms. of Ordinaciones y Paramientos de la Ciudad de Barbastro, a record of Barbastro's late 14th- and mid-15th century ordinances, subsequently edited and published by the historian Mariano de Pano y Ruata in 1905. He appears to have been a man of literary interests: from 1857-1873 he edited the periodical La Exposición de Sobarbe (cf. J.J. Nieto Callén, "La comarca de Somontano de Barbastro durante las Edades Moderna y Contemporánea," p. 123) and his name appears in the subscription list for the second edition of Enriqueta Lozano de Vílchez's Lira cristiana (Granada: Zamora, 1857) and for Saturnino López Novoa's Historia de la muy noble y muy leal Ciudad de Barbastro (Barcelona: Pablo Riera, 1861).] Penn Libraries call number: Inc C-204 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (1861-1943) Established heading: Heron-Allen, Edward, 1861-1943 The bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (17 December 1861 – 28 March 1943), a writer, scientist, and Persian scholar, who produced a literal translation of the Quatrians of Omar Khayyam from the earliest known manuscript, which was in the Bodelian Library of Oxford University [1]. Another biographical sketch of him can be found on website maintained by the Heron-Allen Society [2]. The design elements of the bookplate illustrate a number of his interests. He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in May 1919 for his work in studying the Foraminifera, a class of microscopic amoeboid protists that produce their own shells, sometime with multiple chambers. Hence, the owl (symbol of learning), the microscope, and flanking his name, two examples of Foraminifera (compare to the samples in this photograph). He was an expert in the art of palmistry, and wrote several books on the subject, hence the palms at 9 and 3 o'clock of the circular device. As a young man, he learned the art of violin-making, and wrote a book on that topic, as well, hence the violin in the foreground. He was a scholar of Persian and translated the works of Omar Khayyam, and so Persian written in Arabic script appears in the bookplate, as well. He is also known as the author (under the pseudonym of Christopher Blayre) of The Cheetah Girl, a book that was suppressed because it dealt with themes of unconventional sexuality. Perhaps that is why a naked woman is being contemplated by the man in Persian garb. Given the fact that he wrote numerous books, he is found in VIAF. photo.description: Inscription at head of page: "For Nathaniel Martin Esq. Barrington". There was a Nathaniel Martin of Barrington, Rhode Island. A History of Barrington, Rhode Island, by Thomas Williams Bicknell, mentions a Nathaniel Martin, Esquire of Barrington who was chosen as Colonel of the Bristol County Regiment, and a Colonel Nathaniel Martin who operated a ferry house on the Barrington River in Rhode Island. These are probably one and the same. Penn Libraries call number: AC7 Un33C 774eh All images from this book
